  <!-- HEADER -->
  <div class="subject-header">
    <h1>Thermodynamics</h1>
    <p>
      Thermodynamics is a core mechanical engineering subject that deals with
      heat, work, energy, and their transformations. It forms the foundation
      for power plants, engines, refrigerators, and energy systems.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- INTRODUCTION -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>
      Thermodynamics studies the relationship between heat and other forms of
      energy. It explains how energy moves, changes, and affects physical
      systems. Engineers use thermodynamics to design efficient machines and
      optimize energy usage.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- LAWS -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2>Laws of Thermodynamics</h2>

    <div class="card-grid">
      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Zeroth Law</h3>
        <p>Defines thermal equilibrium and forms the basis of temperature measurement.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>First Law</h3>
        <p>Energy can neither be created nor destroyed, only converted.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Second Law</h3>
        <p>Heat flows naturally from hot to cold bodies; entropy always increases.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Third Law</h3>
        <p>Entropy approaches zero as temperature approaches absolute zero.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- EXAMPLES -->
  <div class="section">
